metadata.name: Calligraphy #149
metadata.description:
Calligraphy is about formulating letters, not language. 

One of my first exercises as a design student (c. 1967) was learning to letter. Using a nib holding pen and India ink we sat for 5 weeks in class like monks constructing letters in the style of a font called 15th Century Chancery Italic Script. Our final grade was based on how well we hand lettered a paragraph. It was a grueling process that's why I remember it; quite the way to develop an appreciation for the letterforms and type faces. 

This algorithmic artwork is modern cuneiform. It is based on a theory I've developed called "Language of Vision" which in itself is an approach for creating a "plastic" image. The space-frame or background square consists of a subtle paper texture and defines the tablet. A resizable tile (spatial force) forms the boundary for a "stroke." The stroke within the tile element is created by joining two bezier curves. 

An algorithm called "fractions of the whole" is a "form of spatial organization" which divides the picture frame into randomly sized intervals along each axes that form the variable sized tile areas. The stroke is programmed to fit each area. This theory lends itself very nicely to algorithmic art and provides a general framework for generative art.

There is meaning in every image but that meaning comes from your experience and imagination.

Check out Dr. Bill Generative Art OG website @ drbillkolomyjec.com

metadata.name: Bored Computer Screen #604
metadata.description:
"Bored Computer Screen" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022


Bored Computer Screen (BCS) is a direct descendant of Specterüëªpixel‚¨õlatte‚òï, where the central idea is agent and displacement. In BCS, there are agents‚Äîthe small moving circles‚Äîthat get their colors ripped away by the surrounding pixels. Though they occur on the same screen space, they are separated in their own cells, a simultaneous multiverse of sorts. In some iterations, a very clear voronoi pattern will appear. I didn't consciously strive for this look. It's what naturally happens, when you try to divide space, so that the borders occur exactly in between the closest neighbor. When I first saw this pattern emerge, I wanted to see how far I could get the distinct cells to influence each other. The idea that the same algorithmic processes can happen many times but still separately in a single piece has always interested me (and explored in the Infinite Browse series). BCS is an extension of that, albeit a little more chaotic.

Note:
- Best experience on browsers and devices with support for WebGL2 

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5, P5Fbo and perlinjs.

metadata.name: Plottable Thousands #46
metadata.description:
'Thousands' explores the packing of recursive circles and golden angle spirals distributing various particles on a A4 canvas.

A SVG file can be exported (right click save) to plot the piece physically.

You can enjoy the digital version that simulate ink effects and optional, thanks to the utility token decoupling, get a physical one: the digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their own materials and ship to collectors ‚Äì as long as NFT is owned at request time.

Code: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-thousands

@greweb ‚Äì 2022 ‚Äì tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM ‚Äì CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

metadata.name: Hatchet: Magarikuneri #110
metadata.description:
Hatchet: Magarikuneri (Êõ≤„Åå„Çä„Åè„Å≠„Çä) is the second piece in Hatchet; a generative art series that hatches an arrangement of segmented polygons generated via a Voronoi diagram. Magarikuneri (Japanese for 'winding/twisting') arranges it's polygons in twisting spirals that are far more chaotic than Hatchet: Uzumaki. The piece will cycle through varying color intensities, resetting upon encountering a twist. There is also a small chance the background will be dark instead of light; allowing for the same palettes to be seen through a different lens.

All pieces in Hatchet are composed to emulate the aesthetic of colored pencils on paper. Each piece is capable of exporting its hatch lines as a well-labeled SVG document. This will allow collectors interested in plotting to create physical renditions of their iteration.

The following key-press actions are supported on the token:
- 'r': Animate the erasure and re-drawing of the hatch lines.
- 's': Export the SVG document describing the arrangement of hatch lines.

metadata.name: X Standout #19
metadata.description:
A minimalist work by Nate Donato featuring a repeating pattern of regular black circles. At least one circle deviates from the norm, marking itself as a standout against the uniformity of the rest. Each small difference is highlighted by the brutal minimalism and regularity of the main circle population, as well as the greater collection body itself.

As a further minimalist exercise, minting of this token was heavily restricted to an exclusive access list including only accounts who held one of the author's three previous fxhash collection works before the scheduled release time (one per account, per collection).


--


Live view controls:

Press [1] to view at native size.
Press [2] to view at large detailed size.
Press [0] to return to default view.

Press [s] to download and save as PNG.
